    <h2>Which Plan Should You Choose?</h2>

    <p>Choosing the right Canva plan depends on how you create visual content, who you're creating for, and what features you actually need. Here's our guidance for different user profiles.</p>

    <h3>Choose Canva Free if...</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>You create designs occasionally — a few times per month</li>
      <li>You don't need premium stock photos, videos, or graphics</li>
      <li>Brand consistency (custom fonts, colors, logos) isn't critical</li>
      <li>You're exploring Canva for the first time and want to test it</li>
      <li>5GB of storage is sufficient for your design files</li>
      <li>You're a student working on school projects</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The Free tier is surprisingly generous. With 250,000+ templates and basic AI tools, it's enough for casual social media posts, simple presentations, and personal projects. The main limitations are storage (5GB fills up quickly if you work with images) and the lack of background removal, Brand Kits, and premium assets.</p>

    <h3>Choose Canva Pro if...</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>You create content regularly — multiple times per week or daily</li>
      <li>You need high-quality stock photos, videos, and graphics for professional work</li>
      <li>Brand consistency matters — you want Brand Kits with custom fonts, colors, and logos</li>
      <li>You use AI features heavily — Magic Write, Magic Eraser, Magic Design, AI image generation</li>
      <li>You need background removal and transparent PNG exports regularly</li>
      <li>1TB of storage gives you room to grow without worrying about limits</li>
      <li>You're a freelancer, marketer, small business owner, or content creator</li>
    </ul>
    <p>At $13/month ($10/month if billed annually), Canva Pro is one of the best value subscriptions in the design software space. The jump from Free to Pro unlocks the full power of Canva — the AI features alone justify the cost for anyone creating content regularly. Compared to Adobe Creative Cloud ($60+/month), Canva Pro is a fraction of the price and far easier to use.</p>

    <h3>Choose Canva Enterprise if...</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>You have 50+ users who need Canva access</li>
      <li>Your organization requires Single Sign-On (SSO) and SCIM provisioning</li>
      <li>You need advanced brand controls — locked templates, restricted fonts, enforced brand guidelines</li>
      <li>Custom approval workflows are required for compliance or quality control</li>
      <li>You want dedicated account management and 24/7 support with SLA guarantees</li>
      <li>Advanced analytics and usage reports are needed for team oversight</li>
      <li>You need unlimited storage and unlimited Brand Kits for multiple departments or brands</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Enterprise pricing is custom-quoted based on user count, storage needs, and required integrations. Most organizations find Canva Enterprise significantly more affordable than enterprise Adobe licensing while offering better collaboration features and a faster onboarding experience.</p>

    <h3>Special Plans: Education & Nonprofits</h3>
    <p>Canva offers two specialized plans worth noting:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Canva for Education</strong> — Free for verified K-12 teachers and students. Includes all Pro features plus classroom-specific tools like lesson plans, student management, and educational templates. Higher education institutions can apply for Canva Campus with discounted pricing.</li>
      <li><strong>Canva for Nonprofits</strong> — Free for registered nonprofit organizations. Provides Pro-level access including Brand Kits, premium assets, and AI features. Verification of nonprofit status is required.</li>
    </ul>

